The Stage of May
London — — Standing before new British Prime Minister Theresa May is a daunting task: to execute the requirements of British voters — — or more specifically, voters in England and Wales — — to withdraw from the EU and manage the far-reaching consequences that come with this task.
The challenge she faces is one that makes her predecessors in recent years pale in comparison.
However, she may have the ability to complete this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has already demonstrated courage in a series of crises, Angela Merkel possesses all the tools she needs to complete the task.
She is smart, resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideology, very skilled at gaining control, and acts within the boundaries she sets for herself to ensure familiarity with the issues at hand.
Angela Merkel has won most of the battles she has participated in, showing no mercy to those who have tried to take her down with underhanded tactics.
But she has few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary party members.
This is a powerful combination — — she needs to fully utilize it to lead the process of Britain's withdrawal from the EU.
The process of Britain's withdrawal from the EU has already begun, which is undeniable.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland vote to stay in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly stated that "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers are all in agreement with her views.
but May has not yet given an accurate definition of Britain's withdrawal from the EU.
This task is extremely difficult to complete.
Imagine someone telling you 'breakfast is breakfast' and then starts preparing your meal.
You find it hard to know exactly what you are going to eat.
A Northern Irish "Ulster Fry" — eggs, bacon, sausages, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomato — paired with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on the environment and personal preferences you are in, you may feel very different about various possible combinations.
The same situation also applies to Brexit.
Some people may be mainly concerned about preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others may be more concerned about obtaining single-market access.
But unlike breakfast, Britain cannot order each dish on the menu.
The reality often ignored by the Brexit camp is that the EU will not give Britain all its benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win people over or punish the UK for refusing the EU (such inflammatory rhetoric is often rampant, such as UK's new foreign secretary Boris Johnson's comment on "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we Britons often forget that everyone - including the EU and all its member states - has its own political or commercial interests to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the next few months will be to determine what Britain's objectives should be, on a realistic basis, after the tough negotiations start on the country's relationship with the EU (and the rest of the world) in trade.
Given the scope of the agenda, which I can think of at least six major themes that need to be negotiated separately, the negotiation process may take years to complete.
(By the time the negotiations are completed, my granddaughter who is 11 years old now may have already started university!)
We must clearly identify our priorities to prevent the negotiation from taking longer.
The goal, of course, is to strike a balance between allowing British goods and services (especially financial services) to enter other European countries and limiting the influx of EU citizens into the UK.
The more concessions you gain in one area, the greater the concessions you will have to make in other areas.
May needs to fully utilize the knowledge, skills, and political capital she possesses to ensure the reasonability of the negotiation transaction.
But even if she can achieve her goals, she will still find people who are dissatisfied not only in one part but in all.
This will further exacerbate the major challenge faced by May's government: bridging the growing gap in British society that has been exposed by Britain's departure from the EU.
The blue-collar workers in northern and central England are the main force behind Britain's Brexit referendum, who have been distant from politicians, marginalized by globalization, and peripheralized by the so-called intermediary - the EU.
The major cities in England - especially London - may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have gained no benefits.
Due to a lack of confidence in Jeremy Corbyn-led Labour Party, many working-class members ultimately became the targets of the populist promises of the Brexit camp.
“We will reverse globalization,” they claim.
“We will chase away the immigrants who depress wages and redirect the hundreds of millions of pounds handed over to the EU to public services,”
They promised that Brexit will bring back a safer and more prosperous past for Britain.
The Brexit camp cannot truly fulfill these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can it be cut off from immigrants from the EU.
Any such actions will only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturn leads to a decrease in immigration, the workers who voted for Britain's exit from the EU may still be disappointed to find that low-paying jobs still have low pay and public services are still under heavy pressure.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has unleashed a populist sentiment storm that is difficult to control.
Just like Donald Trump's inability to improve the living conditions of American working-class voters, Brexit can't bring any benefits to those who chose it, no matter how things look.
Although she has many advantages, it's still unclear if May can overcome this challenge.
